<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="stakeholder-engagement-advanced">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>pm</group>
    <domain>project-manager</domain>
    <summary>Move stakeholders from current to desired engagement level (Unaware to Leading) using Assessment Matrix and evidence-based tactics with drift detection to prevent silent disengagement.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>engagement-levels</tag>
      <tag>stakeholder-movement</tag>
      <tag>evidence-based</tag>
      <tag>change-management</tag>
      <tag>drift-detection</tag>
    </tags>
    <category>pm</category>
    <difficulty>advanced</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-28</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Stakeholder Engagement (Advanced)</title>

    <summary>A structured process for moving stakeholders from their current engagement level (Unaware, Resistant, Neutral, Supportive, Leading) to a desired level through targeted, evidence-based activities. Each engagement level change requires a quoted behavioural signal — not a vibe — as evidence. The core tool is the Engagement Assessment Matrix: per-stakeholder current level, desired level, gap, and a specific activity plan with cadence.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Passive stakeholder lists decay. Resistant stakeholders do not disappear — they become active blockers. Supportive stakeholders lose enthusiasm without maintenance. The five-level model (Unaware to Leading) gives a concrete, auditable measure of relationship health that replaces gut-feel with observable signals (meeting attendance, response time, public statements).</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Stakeholder Register exists but the project lacks champions, has dormant supporters, or active resisters</item>
        <item>Pre-launch and change-management work where adoption depends on department heads</item>
        <item>Long projects (over 6 months) where engagement levels drift — quarterly re-assessment needed</item>
        <item>Coalition-building for portfolio shifts (M&amp;A, reorg, platform migration)</item>
        <item>Public-facing launches where end users are Unaware and need to reach Supportive</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>One-off small tasks with no organisational politics — overhead exceeds value</item>
        <item>Adversarial negotiations (procurement, legal disputes) — engagement implies collaboration; use negotiation playbooks instead</item>
        <item>Crisis communications — different discipline, different cadence and tone</item>
        <item>Projects under 4 weeks with a single decision-maker — a one-page RACI is sufficient</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="engagement-level-definitions">
      <p>Each level is defined by observable behaviour, not assumed attitude. Classification must be evidence-based.</p>
      <list>
        <item>Unaware — no contact, no information received about the project</item>
        <item>Resistant — actively opposes; blocks decisions, escalates concerns</item>
        <item>Neutral — aware but indifferent; neither helps nor hinders</item>
        <item>Supportive — advocates internally; provides resources or air cover</item>
        <item>Leading — drives adoption; removes barriers on behalf of the project</item>
      </list>
      <rule>
        <statement>Classify stakeholder level from behavioural evidence only (attendance, response time, public statements, decisions made). Never classify from assumed intent.</statement>
        <rationale>Polite emails read as Neutral by automated tools and optimistic PMs; actual engagement level is revealed by action, not tone.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="transition-strategies">
      <p>Moving stakeholders between levels requires deliberate, evidence-backed tactics. Each level transition has concrete activities and success criteria.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Move stakeholders one level at a time. Never plan a jump from Resistant directly to Leading — earn each step with a concrete commitment.</statement>
        <rationale>Skipping levels produces shallow engagement that collapses under the first pressure. Resistant stakeholders who feel manipulated regress further.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Resistant to Neutral transition">
        <note>IT Security Director blocking a cloud migration</note>
        <code lang="markdown"><![CDATA[Strategy: address concerns directly, involve in requirements definition.
Activities:
  Week 1: 1:1 meeting — listen, do not defend; document their specific concerns.
  Week 2: Security requirements workshop — they co-author the requirements.
  Week 3: Vendor security certification review session.
  Week 4: Joint sign-off on security acceptance criteria.
Evidence of success: written confirmation of participation in Week 4 sign-off.]]></code>
      </example>
      <example type="good" title="Neutral to Supportive transition">
        <note>Operations Manager on an efficiency project</note>
        <code lang="markdown"><![CDATA[Strategy: demonstrate personal benefit; ask for their input.
Activities:
  - Invite to pilot design session (their domain).
  - Quantify efficiency gains in their team's KPIs, not generic metrics.
  - Ask for their endorsement on the pilot scope document.
Evidence of success: Manager signs pilot scope document or publicly references the benefit.]]></code>
      </example>
      <example type="good" title="Supportive to Leading transition">
        <note>Sales Director at product launch</note>
        <code lang="markdown"><![CDATA[Strategy: give visible role; share strategic information; public recognition.
Activities:
  - Assign speaking role at launch event.
  - Include in weekly strategy sessions (information access signals trust).
  - Feature in internal success story communication.
Evidence of success: Director proactively recruits other supporters without being asked.]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="warning-signals-and-antipatterns">
      <p>Engagement shifts rapidly when warning signs are ignored. Also be aware of common traps.</p>
      <list>
        <item>Declining meeting attendance — disengaging; trigger direct outreach within 48 hours</item>
        <item>Sending a delegate — reducing personal priority; understand the cause before escalating</item>
        <item>Negative public comments — active resistance signal; require private conversation, not email</item>
        <item>Going to executives — escalating concern; address the underlying issue immediately</item>
        <item>Silent in meetings — withholding; follow up 1:1 before the next group session</item>
      </list>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Treating all stakeholders the same — identical email cadence, identical information level.</description>
        <reason>Stakeholders at different levels and with different power need different content, channel, and frequency. One-size comms accelerates disengagement.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Assuming that support earned once is permanent.</description>
        <reason>Engagement decays under competing priorities, project delays, or broken commitments. Leading stakeholders who feel ignored revert to Neutral within weeks.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="assessment-matrix">
      <p>The Engagement Assessment Matrix is the core tool for tracking engagement state and planning interventions.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Build the Engagement Assessment Matrix with columns: Stakeholder, Power (H/M/L), Interest (H/M/L), Current Level, Desired Level, Gap (+/-), and Next Activity.</statement>
        <rationale>The matrix makes engagement gaps visible in one view and drives prioritisation — high power + high gap = highest risk to the project.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Sample assessment matrix">
        <code lang="markdown"><![CDATA[| Stakeholder    | Power | Interest | Current   | Desired   | Gap | Next Activity         |
|----------------|-------|----------|-----------|-----------|-----|-----------------------|
| CEO            | H     | M        | Neutral   | Supportive | +1  | Demo at Board meeting |
| IT Director    | H     | H        | Resistant | Neutral    | +1  | 1:1 concern session   |
| End Users      | L     | H        | Unaware   | Supportive | +2  | Training webinar      |
| Project Sponsor| H     | H        | Supportive| Leading    | +1  | Strategy co-author    |]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="cadence-by-quadrant">
      <p>Apply contact cadence by power/interest quadrant. Over-communicating wastes time; under-communicating allows silent resistance.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Apply contact cadence by power/interest quadrant: Manage Closely (H/H) weekly; Keep Satisfied (H/L) bi-weekly; Keep Informed (L/H) weekly broadcast; Monitor (L/L) monthly summary.</statement>
        <rationale>Over-communicating to low-interest stakeholders wastes time and trains them to ignore messages. Under-communicating to high-power stakeholders allows silent resistance to grow.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="drift-detection">
      <p>Drift is the silent disengagement that only emerges when a stakeholder is needed. Systematic detection prevents surprises.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Flag a stakeholder as drifting when the last recorded interaction exceeds the cadence threshold for their quadrant with no recorded blocker reason.</statement>
        <rationale>Drift is invisible without a system. A stakeholder who was Supportive three months ago may now be Neutral — and will be classified as Supportive in the risk register until someone checks.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>Agents are valuable for evidence collection and gap analysis, but human judgment is required for tactic selection because politics is context-dependent.</p>
      <p>A subagent reads the Stakeholder Register plus recent communications log plus meeting minutes to assess current engagement levels with evidence quotes, identifies gaps to desired levels, and drafts engagement activities per stakeholder. Pair with a meeting-prep helper that produces pre-/post-meeting briefs. Engagement classification must be evidence-based — refuse to upgrade a stakeholder to Supportive without a quoted positive signal. Human-in-loop for tactic selection because politics is contextual; agent proposes, human chooses.</p>
      <list>
        <item>Engagement assessment agent (sonnet): produces engagement assessment YAML with evidence quotes, identified gaps to desired levels, and categorises by power/interest quadrant.</item>
        <item>Drift-detection agent (sonnet): weekly scan for stakeholders whose last recorded interaction exceeds cadence threshold; flags by quadrant.</item>
        <item>Meeting-prep agent (sonnet): produces pre-/post-meeting briefs per stakeholder with concerns, motivations, last interaction, desired outcome, key messages.</item>
        <item>Communications subagent (custom): drafts personalised stakeholder updates from the project status report, personalised by engagement level and past context.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="ai-agent-gotchas">
      <p>LLMs have systematic biases in engagement classification and communication generation. These represent real failure modes.</p>
      <list>
        <item>Polite-tone bias: agents up-rate engagement on courteous emails. Require explicit positive evidence ("agreed to sponsor", "publicly endorsed").</item>
        <item>Translation/cultural cues missed: passive-voice criticism reads as Neutral to LLMs but is Resistant in many cultures. Have human reviewer per region.</item>
        <item>Auto-generated personalised messages can feel canned; require the agent to surface context bullets, not write the email body.</item>
        <item>Meeting-prep agent will pad with generic talking points; force max-3 messages and 1 ask per meeting.</item>
        <item>Do not let agents propose moving Resistant directly to Leading — the Resistant→Neutral hop must be earned with a concrete commitment.</item>
        <item>Privacy: engagement levels are sensitive; never let an agent share level-classification with the stakeholder themselves.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="cli-tools-and-integrations">
      <p>Command-line tools and SaaS integrations provide engagement signals and distribution channels.</p>
      <list>
        <item>gh api — pull GitHub PR review patterns to gauge engagement of technical stakeholders</item>
        <item>slack-cli / Slack API — sample channel activity per stakeholder</item>
        <item>jira-cli — look at comment frequency on tickets owned/watched by stakeholder</item>
        <item>gcalcli — schedule and track 1:1 cadence</item>
        <item>pandoc — render engagement plan to PDF for sponsor review</item>
        <item>Salesforce / HubSpot CRM — use Activity History as engagement signal; REST API available</item>
        <item>Gainsight / Catalyst — customer success engagement scoring; REST API</item>
        <item>Microsoft Viva / Workplace Analytics — meeting time per stakeholder pair (privacy-gated)</item>
        <item>Notion / Airtable — engagement plan plus tracking log; REST API</item>
        <item>Zoom / MS Teams API — pull meeting attendance/duration as engagement evidence</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices">
      <p>Proven practices prevent common failures in stakeholder movement at scale.</p>
      <list>
        <item>Build relationships before you need them — first ask should not be a favour.</item>
        <item>Pre-meeting prep ≥15 min. Personalise: reference the stakeholder's last public statement or initiative.</item>
        <item>Engage resistors face-to-face, not by email — written tone amplifies friction.</item>
        <item>Recognition compounds: public credit for Supportive stakeholders converts them to Leading.</item>
        <item>Track engagement-level history as a time series — trend lines reveal drift the snapshot cannot.</item>
        <item>Pair with Risk Register: a Resistant high-influence stakeholder is a top-tier project risk.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="limitations">
      <p>Be aware of the boundaries and failure modes of the five-level model.</p>
      <list>
        <item>Levels (Unaware to Resistant to Neutral to Supportive to Leading) are not strictly linear; a Leading stakeholder can drop to Resistant if betrayed once.</item>
        <item>Engagement Plans get written and never executed — without rituals (1:1 cadence, status emails) they decay.</item>
        <item>Optimism bias: PMs over-report Supportive. Use behavioural evidence (attendance, response time, public statements) not vibes.</item>
        <item>Hidden stakeholders (auditors, regulators, end users) get neglected because they don't show up; explicit search needed.</item>
        <item>Cultural variance: "Resistance" looks different across cultures (silence vs. open disagreement); single rubric misclassifies.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/engagement-plan.md" purpose="Full engagement plan: assessment matrix + per-stakeholder strategy + activity table"/>
      <template path="templates/meeting-prep.md" purpose="Pre/post meeting brief for a single stakeholder interaction"/>
    </templates>

